Pre-heat your oven to 180 degrees and boil a #pot{} of water. Peel the @potato{1} and chop it into chunks slightly smaller than a golf ball. Peel and slice the @red onion{1/2}(sliced in half through the root, then sliced into thin half moons). Slice the @baby gem lettuce{1}(sliced in half lengthways).

Cook the @British Cumberland sausages{2} on the top shelf of your oven for ~{25%minutes} (turning occasionally). Boil the potatoes until you can easily slip a knife through them. Wrap the @garlic{2%cloves} in a little parcel of #tin foil{} ready to roast later.

> Tip: If you don't have tin foil don't worry, you can roast them just in their skins.

Cook the onions in a #non-stick frying pan{} on medium-low heat with @olive oil{2%tsp}, a knob of @?butter{knob}(if you have some), a pinch of @?sugar{pinch}(if you have some), @salt{}, @pepper{} and the @rosemary{1}. Cook them gently for ~{20%minutes} so that they become soft and sweet - don't burn them!

Mix the @cornflour{1/2} with 2 tbsp of @water{2%tbsp} to make a nice smooth paste and keep this to the side - we'll add it to the gravy later to thicken it up.

About 10 mins after the sausages went into your oven put the little garlic parcel in too. This will slow roast the garlic, making it soft and delicious.

> Tip: If you don't have tin foil just coat the garlic cloves in a bit of olive oil.

Place another #frying pan{} on medium-high heat with @olive oil{4%tsp}. Once hot, place the baby gem lettuce in the pan, sliced-side down. Fry it for ~{3-4%minutes} or until lightly browned.

Once the onions are soft and sweet turn the heat up to medium. Add in 200ml of water and the @chicken stock pot{1/2}, then bring to a simmer. Stir in the cornflour mixture and gently simmer until it thickens up, before turning off the heat.

Once cooked, drain your potatoes and put them back in the pot with the @milk{2%tbsp}, @?butter{4%tsp}(if you have some) and @salt{1/2%tsp}. Squeeze the garlic out of its skin and put this in the pot too. Put the pot on medium heat for ~{1%minute} to dry the potatoes. Mash everything with a #potato masher{} until you have nice lump-free mash.

Serve your mash into #bowls{}, top with your sausages and gravy. Serve your baby gem lettuce on the side. Perfection needn't be complicated.